description.text:
This is a engine mount for the SkyMule so you can use a non bell type engine on it.
I have used the MTN 28-30 1200kv but you can use any BL engine in the 28-30 to 28-35 range. Swapping the engine out is easy.
I have made no holes for mounting the engine because the outcome of the wires of the BL engines are sometimes on different places and they must be coming out on the underside of the pod.
I have printed this in pla, use a thick bottom and top layer when using infill (25%).
ABS is better as some engines can get hot in flight.

description.text:
This is a set of three guitar picks I modeled and printed for a friend for Christmas. YOU NEED TO SCALE!!!!
lay it flat on bed so that any imprints are UP
once it is like that,
long dimension = 30mm
short dimension = 25mm
height = .8mm - 1.3mm depending on desired flex These are almost exactly the size as the popular 351 model guitar picks, the most common type that everyone and their mother use. They have really nice flex at .8mm, I don't know how fragile it would be removing raft at anything below that. One has two stars on it, one is blank, and one has a music note and the word "Music" on it in script MT bold. If you want one with a name instead of "Music", I would be happy to make a custom one, just comment asking me to. If you like this check out my other designs. I also plan to have a GUITAR PICK HOLDER up within the next 12 hours!

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.4mm or below, .2mm recommended

Infill:

100%

Notes: I would recommend rafts. In my experience they peel off otherwise even at 130 degree bed temp. Resolution should be high to get good results, but if you are just printing blank you don't need less than .4mm. I would recommend that for decent quality you do .3mm, high you do .2 or .1mm. YOU NEED TO SCALE!!!!
lay it flat on bed so that any imprints are UP
once it is like that,
long dimension = 30mm
short dimension = 25mm
height = .8mm - 1.3mm depending on desired flex Infill MUST BE 100% or else it will break. They are small and very quick to print.

This is an update to my Preassembled Secret Heart Box, which is smaller and much sturdier. I redesigned the latching mechanism so that it holds much more securely and doesn't wear out. I also designed this so you could easily put two initials on the box using Customizer. 
I find this works quite well as an earring box or pill box, or just as a handy stocking stuffer to fill with small treats. Enjoy!
Note: this is a complex file, so Customizer's preview will time out, but if you click Create Thing, it will properly generate the object.

This box works best when it is slightly fused coming off the print bed. I use an exacto knife to help free it up, first by opening the lid, then separate the two lid pieces, then close it and rotate once the halves are separate. If it's too fused to get moving, enlarge the tolerance slightly in Customizer and reprint.

comments.author: rwojtus

comments.text:
Hi Emmet. Thank you for your advices. I am going to make 0.4 to 0.5mm clearance. Are there any maximum sizes for wall thickness? As I am about to make it 2mm thick. I also notice that if you measure distance between faces ( and measuring line is perpendicular to both measured faces) on that "zigzag" split line it's not actually 0.45mm but circa 0.3mm. Was it done intentionally or is it a sort of error which customisiser can't cope with?
Is there any way to save customised part to STEP file?
comments.author: emmett

comments.text: It was intentional (more or less), as it's mostly clearance in the horizontal plane that matters for FDM. I haven't tested all the possible combos of parameters, so inspect it a bit before you print. Frankly, if you're going to print it in SLS, you might want to pop open the scad file and make a few deeper changes. The main one I can think of is the 45 degree cutoff of the central pin. I needed that to make it FDM printable, but you can keep the whole pin for SLS. Still, I have the feeling it's going to be pretty wobbly when you're done, but I'm curious.

author: TechGirl_Mods

description.text:
This is a set of three guitar picks that designed for my friend as a Christmas gift. One is blank, one has two stars on it, and one has a music note with the word "music" in script MT bold. I broke one when removing it, so be careful YOU NEED TO SCALE!!!!
lay it flat on bed so that any imprints are UP
once it is like that,
long dimension = 30mm
short dimension = 25mm
height = .8mm - 1.3mm depending on desired flex Once you scale this correctly, it almost exactly the same size as the popular 351 style guitar pick. This is the most common style, everyone and their mother use it. This will fit in any guitar pick holder (like the one I will publish later!). The flex at .8mm is really nice. Anything below that may be difficult to remove from rafts. If anyone would like a pick with their name instead of "Music", let me know in the comments and I will be glad to do that for you. If anyone would like any other designs on the pick, I could try them (just comment), or I could upload the inventor file and you could edit it yourself if you have inventor. If you like this, check out my other designs, such as a business card holder, and the pick holder I plan to upload very soon (tonight). Thanks

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.4mm or below, .2mm recommended

Infill:

100%

Notes: YOU NEED TO SCALE!!!!
lay it flat on bed so that any imprints are UP
once it is like that,
long dimension = 30mm
short dimension = 25mm
height = .8mm - 1.3mm depending on desired flex I recommend using rafts, because in my experience they peel off the bed otherwise, even at 130 degrees Celsius. For high quality prints, you will need a high resolution. I recommend .2mm for both the ones with imprints, and .3mm for the blank. You can go up to .4mm, but it won't be great. If you want a very high quality one, such as a long name, .1mm or below if your printer can handle that.

description.text: I have had trouble with the X900 motor mounts breaking, and to replace them with the original pieces I needed to by an entire $30 kit which took forever to ship. So instead of wasting my money on something I could fix I fixed it. I believe these are much more durable than the previous motor mounts, however I have not yet tested their durability. All I know of now is that they fit very nicely on the tricopter maybe with a little sanding, but there is no need to purchase new motor screws because they were designed with all of that in mind. They are however missing the smaller set of holes, because I designed them to fit my motors, but I dont believe somebody would be using the other holes because the frame is so big as it is, but if you want me to upload a smaller hole version just comment about it. These motor mounts are secured at 2 points and use the durability of the thicker material around it to support it.

Modular square tubing tower. Legs are held together by bridges. Make it as tall as you want by printing more pieces.

Select your joint parameters, and keep them constant for all pieces you will print. Tolerance of 0.4 or greater recommended for reasonably easy assembly.  
For each piece, modify the scaffold bottom length and scaffold top length to match the other piece you will attach it to. Height dictates how tall the piece is. Do not exceed your build volume.  
Print as many as you want, but remember that pieces that go on the bottom should be wider so that your tower does not fall over.  
I recommend printing with MakerWare 2.2+ using default LOW profile.

Enjoy the journey I have created these words for 3D printing. The sentences are broken down into words that are designed to stand upright on a shelf. Enjoy.

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

No

No

medium

10

Notes: Important Note: I have experimented with different settings but it is important you get the settings right otherwise the text will not stick to the plate base. Use 4 shells (outside layers) at medium resolution (double that for finer resolution) with 20% infill - these settings are the minimum for providing a firm connection between the text and the base plate otherwise the text will lift off from the base plate. You want it quite strong so that it comes off the bed without breaking apart. I have included each word as a separate file or one can print Lesson1 and Lesson2&3 and get everything in those two prints. It is arranged for a square print volume. As I recall on the individual words I enlarged those to 175%.

author: klaasvaak

description.text:
Note: I had to add the SVG file to be able to publish this. The ODG file is the original. Laser-cut 86.4 (W) x 22.3 (D) x 25.6 cm (H) (34 x 8.8 x 10.1") wine rack from 3-ply 4 mm plywood. You need to cut five pieces:
  • 1 x bottom (with sticks)
  • 2 x front/back
  • 2 x side/roof
    • Observe the correct grain direction (orange double-headed arrow in one of the images) or the thinnest pieces may break. The small-turn-radius dips of the roof require a lot of pressure to get glued properly in place. This could be redesigned for a larger turn radius, but for now it is as it is. To snap to their slots the difficult 1 cm (0.4") wide roof sections on both sides of a dip, apply downwards pressure to the section in the middle of the dip. I used an Epilog Fusion laser cutter with a 1016 x 711 mm (40" x 28") bed. The total cutting time was about an hour at 5% speed. The drawings assume a zero width laser cut, which works OK for plywood, but for plexiglas that probably gives loose joints.

comments.text: I couldn't get this to print properly for the life of me. No matter what I did (glue, hairspray, etc) the first layer slid off. My other prints are fine. I don't get it at all.
comments.author: orange_pla_ftw

comments.text: I can sympathize, I had a lot of trouble printing this initially as well. I would recommend slowing your print speed down as low as your printer will tolerate (at least for the first layer), and then experimenting with extruder temperature and filament type. I got this to work with soft PLA from matterhackers.com at 220C printed at 20 mm/s on a cold glass bed covered with a thin layer of glue stick, but i'm sure it's possible with other filaments, regular PLA or ninjaflex should work fine too. Don't give up!

title: The TARDIS from Doctor Who
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text: This is a detailed 3D replica of the TARDIS from Doctor Who BBC series. You will find 3 parts in this THING: The first is the real size stl model I created based on dimensions from the blueprint I used. The other two are the body and upper part of the TARDIS scaled down for the model having a total height of 11cm and the body emptied for less material to be used. After printing, you can use model glue, super glue or other plastic glue to put it together. Be precise. I recommend that you don't scale the two parts down as the walls are pretty thin and you may experience problems while printing, or damage the model while gluing or painting.

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.19mm (body), 0.09mm (cap)

Infill:

30% (body), 60% (cap)

Notes: I used ABS material. I think that grey color will be best for painting over it.

Painting Use blue spray paint to give the model a nice Tardis-blue look. After a few coats, use model paint to make details such as windows, signs, light, etc. You can also print the signs that the TARDIS originally has and glue them on the model.
Blueprints The model was designed based on a blueprint I found online. Some knowledge was needed to understand it but just checking pictures from the series it was pretty easy to follow.

remixed_from.author: Boardofdenver
remixed_from.title: iPhone 5 wall Stand with speaker cut out

description.text:
Printing an iPhone accessory seems to be a normal thing around Thingiverse. When I stumbled across Boardofdenver's original, whilst looking for iPhone cases, I thought it was clever. Damn clever. There however were three problems I found with the design:

  • It would take up to 8 hours for my MakerBot Thing-O-Matic to print.

  • It had so much extraneous plastic both for support and in the object itself.

  • The cord wraps on the back were difficult to print; requiring more support (wasted plastic) and useless in the mount if it were be designed so the cord would wrap around the plug.
    • I set a few goals for my redesign:
  • Reduce the amount of plastic used in the stand by at least 40%
  • Reduce the amount of support required to print the pieces.
  • Cut the print into two parts allowing for simpler printing.
    • I'm happy to say I delivered after 13 hours of design work from AutoCAD, TinkerCAD and Sketchup. Design Accomplishments:
  • 8+ hour print reduced to 3.9 hours
    Faster with accelerated printers but I have yet to move over to MakerWare and will be building a RepRap derivative soon so I am avoiding it to some degree.
  • 67.3% less ABS plastic used.
    A whopping 27.31% less than what I was designing for.
  • 17% less support material.
    More can be removed over time with creative printing angles. I'm reaching for 25% reduction.
  • Infill reduced to 25% instead of project 30%
    Was experimental put completely successful.
  • 3 Shells reduced to 2.
    Enough strength and thickness for included parts.
    • Next Iteration Goals:

  • Add Sound Amplification Horns
    Horns and/or cups under speaker holes to bounce sound up and away like many seen here on Thingiverse

  • Better Coupling Fit
    Parts holding power brick meet the stand with some spudging and post-processing. The meeting joint is almost 1mm and so relies on KrazyGlue for adherence. I'd like to take adhesive out of the equation all together.
    • On the end it works great. I'm pleased and it serves my purpose well. Thanks Boardofdenver for a really great design.

Derived and remixed with TinkerCad!, Sketchup and AutoCAD 2013. Printed from 3mm natural ABS on a Makerbot Thing-O-Matic Mk 6 Stepstruder and Automated Build Platform running 4.5 Sailfish. 25% infill
.27mm layer height
2 shell
27/27 feedrate

comments.text: I was afraid of that. I didn't expect the reed to be printable, but figured while I was at it to at least show the dimensions of the call I used for reference. I ended up planing a piece of plastic off a super thin cd case (AOL days) for the reed. Most commercial reeds are made from Mylar however if you want something more professional. The insert was finicky, and I ended up using a cork from a bourbon bottle cut to hold the reed. I'll try and fix the insert and re-upload when I get some time. FYSA the call it's based on is pretty low end, and I can't get the back pressure right on the printed one.

description.text:
This is a tricopter I designed whilst wondering how cheaply a tri could be made. I designed it to be a 250 size (250mm diameter circle through motor centers), so that specs between this and 250 size mini-quads would be similar. Disclaimer: I do not have not built this yet, as I do not have a 3d printer, and I have no idea how it handles... If you decide to build this, let me know how it goes and how it handles! That said, here are the "ideal" specs that I calculated from the parts chosen:
Absolute max speed: 72mph (will be less due to air not being an ideal fluid)
Flight time: 7-15 minutes (varies with flight style) Here are the parts I designed around:
Motors (x3)
ESCs (x3)
Naze32 Flight Controller (Unsoldered)
Naze32 Flight Controller (Soldered)
Servo
Battery
Receiver ---This is the one I would use because I have a cheap inexpensive remote (It's actually a really good deal)--- Concerning the propellers, they're cheap, so you might as well get extras... If you're anything like me, you'll need them ;)
Propellers CCW
Propellers CW Additional Parts:
Carbon Fiber Plate (hence the "Carbon" in "Carbon Ninja")
Carbon Fiber Square Tube (10mm x 10mm x 750mm) or Carbon Fiber Square Tube (10mm x 10mm x 300mm)
The round hole in the middle is really important!
Carbon Fiber Round Tube (8mm OD x 750mm) (You could also use wood) x8   -- M3 x 4mm Screws
x4   -- M3 x 8mm Standoffs
x4   -- #6-32 x 5/8" Screws
x17   -- #6-32 x 9/16" Screws
x6 or 12 -- M2 x 14mm Screws You'll also need zip-ties, heat shrink, velcro (1/2" wide for GoPro mount), heat shrink, piano wire (or similar), and connectors to finish it up. There are only four parts that need to be 3D printed: two front landing gear, one rear tail landing gear/servo mount, and one tail boom control arm mount.

When was the last time you got to toot on a turd? Well, today's your lucky day! This is an ocarina in the shape of the poop emoji. You can also use it as a Christmas tree ornament by stringing it through the tone hole. If you paint it with texture paint as I did, it will likely no longer work. I'd recommend printing it with earth-colored filament (followed by acetone vapor treatment) instead. Given its shape, it shouldn't be any surprise if it sounds like crap, but it's still a lot of fun for the kids and makes for a very novel decoration. Here's a 'scale': https://youtu.be/n77WwJD3vPk Nonetheless, here are my other non-unchi-laden ocarinas: large 6-hole:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1012353 small 5-hole:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1035794 medium 4-hole (most tone-accurate):

I made a lamp stand for my niece who has a name with a J, so I decided to design it like a J.
The lampshade fits for a E27 light bulb. I used a E27 mount with a M10x1 thread. I divided the stand into pieces because I can only print things up to 200mm height. Please rotate the parts into the best position for your printer.

• Pull a wire through the "pipes"
  • Connect the pipes and the thread for the E27 mount together
  • Connect the wire to the E27 mount
  • Tighten the E27 mount
  • Connect the wire to the switch and the plug

• Switch (I used something like this: http://www.kabelscheune.de/Textilkabel-Stoffkabel/Schnurschalter-10-A-Zwischenschalter-schwarz.html?adword=PLA&gclid=CNrn4bmg88kCFUHnwgodxvgLSQ)
  • Plug (I used something like this: http://www.voelkner.de/products/174395/Schutzkontakt-Stecker-Vollgummi-IP44.html?ref=43&products_model=X91778&gclid=CK7T3tOg88kCFcaVGwod73QDlQ)
  • E27 mount (I used something like this: http://www.leuchtenbau24.de/de/fassungen-u.-halter/e27-fassungen)

title: Micro 105 FPV Quadcopter - 8.5mm Motors, Micro Scisky
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This frame was inspired by the FireFlo V2 and the Alpine Drones Micro H. My goals were to keep it crash resistant, light weight and offer good protection for onboard gear. It measures ~105mm. The V1 frame weighs ~10g and the V2 frame weighs ~8g when printed in PLA. My full build (currently V2 base and V1 top) weighs ~38g without the battery. It is designed around 8.5mm motors and the Micro Scisky flight controller. The camera mount is angled up 13 degrees to accommodate fast forward flight.

Guide to configuring the Micro Scisky
See the full build instructions on instructables.

• Flight Controller: You need a Flight Controller with a receiver that matches your radio. I list radio options for the different protocols below.
    • Eachine F3 FrSky
    • Eachine F3 FlySky
    • Eachine F3 DSM2
    • FlySky Micro Scisky
    • FrSky Micro Scisky
    • DSMX/DSM2 Micro Scisky. You might need to remove the motor plugs from this one in order to fit inside the frame.
  • Motors: Hubsan X4 H107c 8.5mm Motors
  • Battery: I use a mix of a few batteries. 380mAh Hubsan, 500mAh Hubsan and 300mAh Nano-Techs CAUTION: When using the Nano-Techs, make sure the battery polarity is correct. I have had to switch the connector position on these.
  • Props: I am currently using Ladybird props. They hold up a lot better than the Hubsan props.
  • Battery Pigtail: I cut one of the leads off of a charging adapter.
  • Nylon Hardware: M3 nylon nuts and machine screws. I used the 20mm machine screws and cut them to size after attaching to the frame.
  • Printable Standoff And Clip: As an alternative to using nylon hardware, navyblueboss made a very nice pin and clip set. I have not yet printed a set of these but they look great.
  • JST SH Connector: A JST SH connector can be used to get get a 5v supply for fpv gear straight from the Scisky. CAUTION: I managed to fry the power supply on one of my Scisky boards. Other users have reported the same when using the FC to power FPV gear. Another option is to use straight battery power or a voltage regulator from battery for VTX and camera.

There are a few new options for an all in one FPV setup. You can connect these straight to battery power and don't need a voltage regulator. These camera and video transmitter modules can be used with the v4 frame. Here are a few options that I have tested with.
  • FX798T
  • FX797T

These components will allow you to build the FPV setup yourself. These components are for v1, v2, and v3 frames.
  • VTX: FX758-2 5.8G 200mW Video Transmitter
  • Antenna: I used the inner wire from the coaxial cable of a broken clover leaf antenna. I used the default frequency on the FX758-2 which is 5865. After soldering the wire on, I cut the antenna to 12.8mm which is the quarter wavelength of that frequency
  • Camera: 170 Degree Wide Angle Camera
  • 5v Step-Up Voltage Regulator: Use a pololu 5v step-up instead of the JST SH connector to avoid burning up the voltage regulator on the Scisky.

You need a radio that matches the protocol of your FC. Here are some options for a few protocols.
  • FlySky
    • FlySky FS-i6
    • FlySky FS-i6X
  • FrSky
    • Taranis Plus
    • Taranis QX7
  • DSM2/DSMX
    • Spektrum DX6i
    • Spektrum DX5e
    • FsFly T-Six

• Eachine EV800 Goggles - These are inexpensive goggles that can double as a standalone screen. These would make a good pair of starter goggles.
  • Fatshark Dominator V3 Goggles + Receiver Module

People have had success transplanting the flight controller and motors from a Hubsan X4 H107C. Going this route, you would get motors, flight controller, a battery, a radio and a set of props for relatively cheap. You could then add FPV with a camera, VTX and a voltage regulator. I have not tried this route yet, but plan to build one soon for a friend. I will post my results when I do.

• 1/9/2016 - Added bottom-v2-experimental. I was able to reduce the weight of the bottom of the frame to ~5.5g. This saves ~1.5g from v1. I don't think the frame durability will be affected much.
  • 1/10/2016 - Added top-v2-experimental. I was able to reduce the weight of the top of the frame to ~2.3g. This save ~0.5g from v1. The v2 top and bottom combined should be ~8g when printed in PLA. Both the v2 top and bottom will feel a bit flexy separately, but once they are connected the quad will feel solid but still allow some give in crashes. I recommend using M3 nylon hardware to secure the pieces together. I do not anticipate the v2 top compromising durability in any way. NOTE: I have printed, but not flown with this top. My camera is hot glued to the v1 top so I will need to find some time to make the switch.
  • 1/11/2016 - Added top-v2-no-cam-experimental. I've been doing some indoor LOS flying and wanted to see how it preformed without the FPV gear. Wow, there is a lot of pop.
  • 1/16/2016 - Added top-v2-cam-down-7. This points the camera down 7 degrees. In order to clear the base plate, I had to push the camera forward just a bit and I made the standoffs of cam-down 1mm taller so the camera does not extend below the bottom plate. I also removed the word "experimental" from v2 filenames.
  • 5/9/2016 - Added bottom-v3. This version should be much stronger than v2 but it weighs only ~0.2g more. I was able to increase the thickness of the arms while saving some weight with a few other modifications. I also added some relief to the back to make it easier to plug a USB cable into the Scisky.
  • 7/25/2016 - Added v4 top and bottom which allow for all in one FPV modules. The bottom has hooks for an underslung battery and the top has a recessed seat for the FPV gear. I also added a 7mm version of the v4 bottom. I did not test the 7mm version as I don't have any 7mm motors. Please let me know how it works if you use this frame.
https://youtu.be/qZ-qDsXewZI

Infill: 100%
Layer Height: 0.3mm
Bottom Piece: 4 Perimeters
Top Piece: 2 Perimeters
Extrusion Width: 0.4mm for all tops and v1, and v2 bottoms. 0.48mm for v3 and v4 bottoms. I optimized the dimensions to be all perimeters hoping that it makes it stronger.

comments.text: thanks. but what happend if the C rating is to high or to low
comments.author: punkkills

comments.text: The C rating is how much current you can draw from the battery related to it's capacity.  If you have a 500mAh battery, rated at 25C you can expect to be able to draw a sustained 12.5A from the battery (.5 * 25).  If you have a 40C on the other hand, you could pull 20A.  It is important that you can feed those motors the current that they want.  I can tell a large difference in available thrust between the hubsan replacement batteries and the nano-tech batters that I link to.  You can't ever have a C rating that is too high :).  The fact that those batteries don't even list a C rating would be a red flag for me.

comments.author: punkkills

comments.text: Since it gets worse over the battery life time, I'm wondering if heat and/or voltage drop could be an issue.  The vtx I link can get pretty hot.  It needs good air flow for cooling from the props while flying.  You also want to keep that heat away from the voltage regulator which is making its own heat.

comments.text: Well i made some new discoveries. I splitted the power of the scisky and the video gear, so basicly I have two saparated batteries, one for each. This way there cant be a voltage drop. Guess what, no noise, no blacks, no nothing. Just an great picture.

comments.text: Did you set min throttle at cleanflight? It is possible, that your tx on lowest position of throttle is still too high. So the CF didnt recognize, that throttle is at min and it do not allow you to arm.
comments.author: qiyanglu

comments.text: you are on the right track, but it is min_check not min_throttle.  min_throttle is the throttle command that the FC will send to the motors/ESCs once min_check has been passed with a physical throttle stick value.  The FC will not arm if the throttle stick value is above min_check.

comments.text: What kind of plastic should be used on this print?
comments.author: Ophidian

comments.text: Good question, I should probably add it to the description.  I would recommend ABS.  It should be pretty durable but still rigid enough for a good tune.  PLA works well but it will break more easily in a crash.  I printed a few in PETG and while it held up well in crashes, the flexibility made it very hard to tune.
comments.author: Ophidian

comments.text:
There are may different filament types, fortunately. I am currently using HIPS, high impact polystyrene, which prints like PLA. You need to run the head about 225C, and the buildplate around 55C. Its cheaper than ABS, and more durable than PLA. One word of caution about nylon....ok it might be a few words....is that it is hygrophobic, which I think means its likes to absorb water. So you need to keep it dry, and if its been sitting out awhile needs to be baked in a small oven at around 125 for a few hours. If not, the moisture in it makes bubbles and the extrusion will be nasty ( you can actually hear the water/air pop as the filament is extruded).
I have carbon infused, magnetic, conductive, wood filled, coffee scented, steel, and flexible to play with!!! Also some PETT, clear PET, and the nylon..of course.

comments.text: Sorry, there is no build guide. You might want to start without FPV gear and get the quad running. The build is relatively simple. Solder the motors to the correct solder pads with the correct polarity and solder on a battery connector. The banggood page for the motors has details about motor rotation and polarity based on the wire colors. You might want to reference a cleanflight motor diagram for the rotation (http://forum.flitetest.com/attachment.php?attachmentid=41041&d=1424292878). Next bind your radio. The more challenging part will be configuring the flight controller. Search for "cleanflight tutorial", there are plenty of resources.

comments.text: Are you doing anything to secure the motors, or just friction fitting them?
comments.author: Mercy404

comments.text: I found that when printing in PLA, they would be tight at first, but over time would become a bit looser.  I suspect this might be from the PLA becoming soft from heat from the motors.   I ended up putting a small amount of electrical style tape (I have some thinner rolls) around the bottom of the motors.  I would cut a small piece and wrap under the bottom cap and up the sides.  I then would trim off the extra tape sticking up over the motor mounts once fitted. That helps hold them in place and you might even need to use a screw driver to open up the slot a bit when fitting them.
comments.author: Mercy404

comments.text: Cool, thanks! I had the frame printed by a few different services, the one from Shapeways that was polished easily fit the motors with a little bit of force, the ones from local printers on 3DHubs I had to sand down the inside of the motor mounts a bit to get them to fit at all, but in both cases I've wondered how they'll hold up over time. I've used some heatshrink on the outside of the motor and mount like the 3DFly on one of them, I'm going to see how that holds up before trying some other methods. The heatshrink added about 0.65g.

Not a flight but a crash :)
the frame is pretty resilient but eventually everything gives.

I have heard of breakages from others but I have yet to break a frame myself, even printed in PLA.  It is important to try and get the arms to be all perimeters and no infill.  The arms are 2.4mm wide so if you specify 0.4mm extrusion width and at least 3 perimeters, the arms will be all perimeters with 6 in total.

comments.text: How does PLA work with this little guy? Is PLA holding up to the normal wear and tear, "landings" etc? Im looking at my first 3D printer and the PLA only models are more in my price range.
comments.author: jk6stringer

comments.text: PLA has been working great for me.  I have only printed this in PLA and with a handful of hard crashes, I haven't broken a frame yet.  The curved arms allow some flex to absorb impacts.  Even in PLA I can bend the side arms to touch the FC tray without any undo stress in the model.  I would imagine that something more flexible like ABS, PET+ or Nylon might be a bit more resilient.  In the event of a broken frame, it is super easy to swap the flight components from the base, so just print a few extras just in case and you will be good :D.

title: da vinci EASY BED calibration remix for FlashForge

description.text:
I really like  theaguie's Da Vinci dial indicator mount (thing:718768) , but it didn't quite work on my FlashForge Creator Pro.  I needed to modify it a bit to keep it from dragging on the X drive belt.  It also needed to be higher off the build plate so my probe only had about a mm of travel.  The spring from the indicator can actually deflect the build plate if it is compressed too much.
While I was at it, I also made the hole large enough for the 9.5 mm diameter shaft of my digital indicator.  Actually, I made it just a hair too big, but found that if I wedge it with a bit of extruded filament, it works perfectly.  Not enough of a bother for me to worry about.
In the picture, the red thing is the original design.  The black one is my remix.
Just a light touch with a round file on the rail mounts so it slides easily on the rails.

EDIT: I would no longer use this. Blower fans are much better for cooling PLA as they support a higher pressure differential. Try my new design.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2155007 This is an improved PLA cooling fan mount for the kossel clear fan mount. It accepts 2 X 40 mm fans for cooling the PLA, and one 30 mm fan for cooling the extruder. If you get the thin 40 mm fans you can mount them to the inside. In this configuration the fans have almost no impact on your printable area. Also, the other designs with the 40 mm fans on the same side always seemed to not cool the pla as well if the corner was on the opposite sides. Since this design has the fans 180 degrees apart, i am hoping it works better. Just starting to try it now. I recommend this fan duct for the extruder, even though the nut area seems to always be too small when i print it. I just drill it out and or ABS glue the nut in.

description.text: This is a stipple drawing of a photograph of a Melita teapot of the same style as the Utah Teapot. It is drawn on an ornament using the EggBot. The ornament shown is 2.6 inches in diameter and the pen used was a 0.2 tip Copic Multiliner SP.

This is a DIY modification to add Sky-Commander digital setting circles to a Skywatcher 10" collapsible Dobsonian telescope.

Printer:

Flashforge Creator

Resolution:

.2mm/layer

Infill:

70%

Steps I followed to install Sky-Commander on my Skywatcher USA 10" Collapsible Dobsonian Proceed at your own risk. This installation does require modification to the base board of your Skywatcher USA Dobsonian mount and it is not a reversible operation. These parts have been designed by me for use on my Skywatcher USA 10" Collapsible Dobsonian telescope with white base. No other Skywatcher mounts have been tested, but I suspect the 8" and 10" models will both be fine. The 12 - 16" models may have different bolt patterns and you might not be able to follow these steps exactly. Step 1 - Order the stuff. I ordered two kits from www.skyeng.com. The two kits you need are SYS-XP-4000 ($410 at the time of this writing) and ALT-AZ-1000 ($60 at the time of this writing). Step 2 - Go to Lowes or Home Depot at buy a single M10x1.5x40mm bolt. I got mine at Lowes for $0.92 Step 3 - Print out the parts in this thing. There are 4 parts total in the file. They are 1 - ALT bearing coupler adapter, 2 - Base Bushing, 3 - ALT encoder arm base, 4 - ALT encoder arm insert. I printed mine in ABS at .2mm layers and 70% infill. Step 4 - Base modification. Remove the optical tube and disassemble the baseboard from the base of the mount. Using a drill with a hole saw bit that matches the size of the Sky Engineering supplied base bearing, drill out the center hole for the new bearing. Be careful to keep the hole saw centered to avoid offset spinning in the AZ path. Even if it's slightly offset it should not matter as long as the axis of rotation does not wobble. Step 5 - Base reassembly. Re-assemble the mount base to the base board in the same manner as shown in the Sky Engineering manual page 48 (as of this writing) with one exception. Add the 3D printed base bushing to the nut before inserting it to remove the lateral slop that you would have without the bushing. Step 6 - Assemble the ALT Bearing encoder coupler assembly. Place the M10x1.5x40mm bolt in the base of the ALT bearing coupler adapter. Screw the Sky Engineering supplied ALT coupler into the adapter by lining up the screw holes and the slot for the nylon lock screw. Step 7 - Remove the right side T-handle from the ALT bearing and replace it with the ALT bearing encoder coupler assembly. Tighten as tight as you can with your hands. When you tilt the tube up and down, you should still see free spinning action for this bearing. This is critical for the encoder to read the ALT adjustments. Step 8 - Remove the topmost right side allen bolt from the mount and insert it into the ALT encoder arm base and re-attach it to the mount. Step 9 - Insert the ALT encoder arm insert into the recess of the ALT encoder arm base. This should be snug but hand removable. Step 10 - Slide the end of the ALT encoder arm onto the notched part of the ALT encoder arm insert. Align and insert the ALT encoder shaft into the coupler and tighten down the nylon set screw. Step 11 - Line up the end of the AZ encoder arm with the left or right side of the mount and insert the shaft into the AZ coupler in the base. Tighten the nylon set screw. In my case, the arm was the perfect length to reach the sidewalls of the mount without having any play and it did not bind the encoder. Step 12 - Cable up the ALT and AZ encoders to the Sky-Commander unit. Step 13 - Once you have confirmed everything is operational, route the cables as desired and attach the Sky-Commander to the desired location on the mount or OTA.

This quick and dirty bracket allows you to use the excellent Diiicooler on your stock FolgerTech 2020 i3 extruder (or anything else with the same heat break)
The fit isn't absolutely perfect but it works fine. There are a couple mm of clearance on all sides of the hot end.
There is a 3mm angle where the bracket meets the DiiiCooler to counteract the heating cartridge/thermistor wires pushing the cooler down. Holes are oversized 1mm so you can make small adjustments before tightening all the bolts.
There are a few mm of clearance to the nozzle tip. To adjust in in either direction just add a few washers on either the heat break side or the Diiicooler side, depending on which way you want it to go.
Requires 2x M3 bolts plus the hardware listed for the DiiiCooler, 6 mm or longer will do. I used 20mm because that's what I have on hand.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Folger 2020 Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm (not critical)

Infill:

20-30%

Notes: Printed on my FolgerTech 2020 i3 with some cheap unknown ABS that my friend gave me for free. This probably won't end well with PLA but you can try. Other plastics should be OK too.

Every Christmas season I have been setting up a lighted tunnel over the sidewalk in front of our house. It is essentially 1/2" PVC tubing that is connected together to provide a skeleton structure to hang the lights from (see uploaded pictures for context). The neighborhood kids love it since it is a Christmas decoration they can "interact" with by walking through it.
This year when I was hanging the lights, I used over 100 zip ties to secure the lights to the pvc tubing. I felt this was rather wasteful since I would not be able to reuse them, and everything else about the setup is reusable year-to-year. And when hanging lights from our house we have reusable plastic hooks that connect to our gutters and secure the light strands. So, I decided to design my own hooks that would be compatible with the 1/2" PVC tubing. It took me a little time and prototyping, but I have something that seems to work pretty well. Next year I am going to print my hooks in white or natural PLA or HIPS and use them to hang all the lights on the PVC structure.
There are two files:
half_inch_pvc_hook_small.stl - This is a hook that attaches to the 1/2" PVC tubing and has a space to hold a single strand of lighting wire (~8 mm circular area).  It just snaps onto the tubing over the lighting wire.
half_inch_pvc_hook_large.stl - This is the same as the small one (still fits the 1/2" PVC tubing) but it has a larger space to hold two strands of lighting wire (~10 mm of circular area).

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Standard

Notes: I printed mine in "beginner" mode in Cura using HIPS. It is flexible enough to open and snap around the PVC tubing. I think PLA would work just as nicely.
I used OnShape (www.onshape.com) to create the 2D sketch of the shape and extruded it. Then exported an STL file of the result.

description.text: Just a basic Carbon Filter with a 14 mm male and female.  When the bulb is filled with active carbon, it really filters anything passing through it.  Has a built in screen also.  Attempt at your own risk, I would definitely advise PLA because it's more natural and doesn't have the harsh chemicals of ABS but I seriously doubt that it would get hot enough for any chemicals to be released from the plastic. The most recent one I printed fit enough to work but wasn't perfect so I messed with it a bit.  Didn't modify the helix one so that will be a little loose on the male and too tight on the female but can certainly still work.  Once printed just get some activated carbon, I got my from the fish tank section of Petco, put it in, rinse the carbon and you're good to go.

Notes: They can print just fine without any supports. The helix wrapped one gets a bit sloppy when the helix first starts but its easy enough to clip the drooping filament after the print, everything else comes out well. The other two should come out no problem without support too.

Lightweight FPV case for the Turnigy Action Camera. Much less weight than the waterproof case. No supports needed to print. Uses two M2.4 or M2.5 bolts for the back and two for the lens cover (available online or Home Depot). Print the layer lens section in black to reduce reflection on camera lens. Cut and drill two holes into a small piece of plexiglass / acrylic / polycarbonate (Lexan) or whatever clear plastic you have. The case has holes allowing access to all of the buttons and USB charging port. This case does cover the SD card slot (as I lost an SD card in a hard crash with a Mobius). The back panel has a cut-out allowing the LED indicators to be seen. Attach with a strap or velcro (I use 3M Dual-Lock).

This is a Cheap and easy alternative to GoPro gimbals such as the Steadicam Curve.
It uses AUD 10 cent coins as a counterweight, if anyone wants to modify the models to fit different weights or currencies, feel free to do so. I recommend printing the handle and the weight with 0.3mm layer height and 1.2 shell thikcness and top/bottom height with 20% infill and the GoPro mount with these same settings except with 100% infill I use about 600mm of 16mm dowel for the rod. I don't know what size nuts or bolts i used but one nut and bolt is the same size as a normal GoPro bolt and the second nut and bolt is a bit larger to hold the weight on the dowel. The Gopro mount and handle should press fit and easily hold the weight of everything, if not some sanding and filling to get a snug fit.

title: Weighted Christmas Stocking Holder with Yoda

description.text:
I needed a Stocking holder for my mantel since we broke one of our old ones. I hate going
out to the malls this close to Christmas, so I decided to make one. The holder consists of a
base that you fill with anything heavy (I used BB's); a lid that you glue on top of the base; and
a hook that glues into the slot in the front of the base. I made the hook a tight fit, so you may
need to scale it down a bit depending on your settings. I also resized 19baeD's Christmas Yoda to scale matching the base. It just glues in place.
You can really use any flat bottomed model with this base, I just thought Christmas Yoda
looked nice on it..

Printer:

Printrbot Simple V1

Rafts:

No

Resolution:

.2mm

Infill:

15%

Notes: Print all things as oriented. Yoda and the hook need support, but the others do not.

Fill and Assemble Dry fit all parts to ensure smooth assembly
Fill the base with something heavy. I used BB's to fill mine.
Glue the lid onto the base, covering the added weight
Slide the hook into the slot in the base and glue in place

description.text: Made the Link's sword and shield from the Legend of Zelda for my brother on his birthday. He absolutely loved it! Scale and print as you wish!

title: Spring foot for eagle (prosthetic) - Atomic Lab

description.text:
I got the inspiration from the paralympic riders legs, the goal is to be printed on ABS or PLA and have a little elasticity from a tough material. It MUST be printed lying to enhance the spring effect and does not break easily.
Special thanks to Emanuel for ask the design.
Gino Tubaro - Atomic Lab 24/12/2015. Happy Navidad!

Printer Brand:

Up!

Printer:

Up Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

It doesn't matter at all

Infill:

This should be the 65% solid.

Notes: I repeat, It MUST be printed lying to enhance the spring effect and does not break easily.

comments.text: Hi!, my name is Antonio and I am writing from Madrid (Spain). I'm looking for prosthesis for my bird, an American Kestrel and I can not find anything. I think it can help a lot my bird that had an accident. Do you think that your design can help me?. Do you think simply scaling the design to smaller would work?. I'm not a designer. You can help?Thank you so much for everything.

Voronoi style remix of the "Holiday Christmas Deer".

This is a mount that I came up with to mount my E3D V6 Hot ends. I needed something that would allow me to adjust the elevation of each hotend relative to each other to make sure that I have the nozzle tips the same distance off the bed. You will need to print two of the clamps. The body is one file but contains two parts split with a 0.2mm gap. STEP files are also uploaded for easy modifications.
Hardware:
4x #6-32 Square nuts
2x #6-32 SHCS Screws x 0.75"
2x #6-32 SHCS Screws x 1.0"
7x M4 Screws x (However long you need them to mount) Used for mounting to bracket
For the hinge pin just use a section of 1.75 filament. EDIT: The qty for square nuts has been changed from 6 to 4 as the two that are shown in the top section are not required even though they are shown in the renderings. You will notice that in the photo if it mounted to the machine they are not present.

Printer:

ORD Bot Hadron

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

50%

Notes: I printed mine with 50% infill and a solid layer every 20 layers for added strength. I also printed with 5 top and bottom layers and 5 perimeter layers.
I used the Concentric external fill pattern to get a nice smooth top and bottom surface finish.

comments.text: Like this very much, had an issue with the clamps breaking at the hinge point, next time will secure the screw before inserting the pin as the E3D fit tight and maybe if i had trimmed the clamp mount a little ( was a clean print) just a tad too big,great idea making a mount for the extruder plate  so i can test in a couple of weeks
comments.author: recoush

comments.text: For the pin what I ended up doing was just using a piece of 1.75mm filament and it worked better than the printed pin.  I should have updated the description to note that.  I designed it to fit tight because I did not want the hotend to be able to move at all once clamped but you are right the hinge point is a bit thin.  Perhaps I should do another one where the hinge is on the outsides and could have more material.  I used mine for a long time but now have moved on to another design that allows me to quickly swap out hotends in just seconds so that I can have them already set up with different nozzle sizes.  I plan on posting it also once I get all the kinks worked out. =)
comments.author: recoush

comments.text: Working on a remix of this for my ord bot hadron and had a question on the height adjustment bar across the top.  I noticed the stl has a nut trap, but your printed part doesn't appear to have them.  When thinking about it in my head (I'm sure I'm just being stupid) it would seem if there was a nut on each part that when you adjusted the distance between the two nuts would remain the same and the screw itself would just come out.  Some clarification would be appreciated.
comments.author: jneilliii

comments.text: You are right, I forgot all about that.  I realized that with that nut in the top bar you would not be able to adjust the height of the hotends as the screw would just tighten down on the top bar making it useless.  I eliminated it and must have forgotten to upload a new file.  Your thinking is right on the money =)
comments.author: jneilliii

comments.text: Thanks for the quick response. I'll definitely post my remix and give proper credit.
comments.author: cdl1701

comments.text: Did you ever end up modifying this to support a part cooling fan as well?
comments.author: atreidae

comments.text: I did but it removes the Z-Probe sensor and cuts the aluminum leg off where the sensor is at.  If you are not using the ORD Hadron then that may not be a big deal.  I can upload that part if you like
comments.author: atreidae

comments.text: I love my Hadron, its been through a ton of modifications but I still have the original "L" bracket on mine, I hacked one up for a build I did for someone else.
comments.author: cdl1701

comments.text: Same with mine. I am in the process now and testing a new hotend assembly that allows two colors to be extruded through the same E3D V6 AND the hotend is able to be quick swapped by pulling a module out and a new one in.  I am doing this so I can have multiple hotend modules set up with different nozzle sizes.  Almost have all the bugs worked out of it and will post it in the next few weeks.  It has an integrated part cooling fan, LED light ring, and will have the ability to add a BLtouch.
comments.author: atreidae
